        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{lamb-shoulder}}, {{chickpeas-tinned}}, {{tinned-tomatoes}}, {{dried-apricots}}, {{onion}}, {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{ras-el-hanout}}, {{cinnamon-ground}}, {{turmeric}}, {{tomato-puree}}, {{honey}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}} to the slow cooker. Pour in the {{stock-chicken}} and stir to combine. Add the {{preserved-lemon}} rind if using. Cook on low for 6 to 8 hours, until the lamb is completely tender. Taste and adjust the seasoning, the sauce should taste warm, slightly sweet, and deeply spiced. Serve over couscous with a dollop of Greek yoghurt.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Fry the ras el hanout, cinnamon, and turmeric in a small splash of oil in a pan for 1 minute before adding to the slow cooker. Spices lose potency quickly, replace if they are more than a year old",
              "cause": "Spices not bloomed before going in, or ras el hanout is old",
              "symptom": "Tagine tastes bland despite the spices"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add a squeeze of lemon juice and taste. The preserved lemon rind also balances sweetness if you have it available",
              "cause": "Apricots are very sweet, or too much honey",
              "symptom": "Sauce too sweet"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Continue for another hour. Lamb shoulder needs the full cook time to break down the collagen in the connective tissue",
              "cause": "Diced smaller than 4 cm or cooker running cool",
              "symptom": "Lamb tough at 6 hours"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Moroccan lamb tagine has become a British dinner party and midweek standard. The slow cooker version requires no monitoring and produces a deeply flavoured result that would otherwise need a full afternoon on the hob. It keeps well in the fridge for three days and reheats without deteriorating.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
